                    <li>The Mexico City International Airport, known to officials as the Benito Juarez International Airport, serves over forty-eight million passengers travelling to and from the Greater Mexico City region every year. </li>
                    <li>The Pisa International Airport, also known to travellers as the Galileo Galilee Airport, provides service to over five million passengers travelling to and from the region every year from its location in the Pisa city. </li>
                    <li>The Cape Town International Airport, located at a distance of twenty kilometres or twelve miles from the city, provides service to over ten million passengers travelling to and from the city every year. </li>
                    <li>The Montreal Trudeau International Airport, also known to locals as the Montreal Dorval International Airport serves over twenty-one million passengers travelling to and from Montreal every year from its location in the Dorval city at a distance of twenty kilometres or twelve miles from the downtown area of the city. </li>
                    <li>The Narita International Airport, known to some travellers as the Tokyo Narita International Airport and in earlier times as the New Tokyo International Airport is located in Narita city at a distance of sixty kilometres or thirty-seven miles from the city centre and provides service to over thirty-two million passengers travelling to and from the city every year.</li>
                </ol>
                <h3>Some essential things to bring along on a trip</h3>
                <p>One of the most important objects that all travellers must carry when they make a trip to these locations of cultural importance is a good camera that allows them to capture their memories as well as the new facts they may learn about the location. </p>
